  "analysis": "The main tension is (a) a genuinely clean, broad-based Q4 beat with explicitly bullish CEO commentary and a FY26 guide that implies ~10% EPS growth, versus (b) a ~20% pre-earnings rally from November lows and a Q1 FY26 Adj EBIT margin guide of -60 to -100 bps due to tariff pass-through. The long side wins on three grounds. First, this setup is structurally the inverse of Q3_FY2025's -12% reaction: comps here are +4% on a +6% stack (strong absolute and vs own trend), whereas the Q3 miss was driven by comps trailing off-price peers. Second, the direct off-price peer base rate is unambiguously positive — ROST printed a comparable clean beat and reacted +7-8% adjusted; specialty peers (ANF -4%, LULU +4%) are not the right analog per the Q4_FY2024 lesson. Third, non-recurring items (layaway +$12.7M gain, security-tag -$11.7M write-off) roughly offset inside Adj EPS, so the $4.99 print is not inflated by one-time gains. The Q1 margin guide-down is a real headwind but is explicitly tariff-mechanical, not demand-driven, and is paired with a healthy +2-4% Q1 comp guide. The pre-earnings rally and the lack of FY26 consensus visibility (data gap) keep this out of the high-confidence bucket, and the reserve-inventory mix being down 6pp (40% vs 46%) weakens the 'hidden margin upside' case relative to the Q4_FY2024 playbook. Net: direction long, confidence 68, expected range 2.0-5.5%, centered around 3-4% — below ROST's +7% because BURL enters with more beta burned off in the rally and with a visible Q1 margin drag that ROST's print did not carry.",
